 (1) Executive Summary (100+ words)

This analysis is based on the Titanic dataset, which contains passenger information such as age, sex, passenger class, fare, family relationships, and survival status. The main objective of this project was to identify patterns that influenced survival and to prepare a clean, feature-rich dataset suitable for machine learning modeling. Through exploratory data analysis and feature engineering, several important insights were discovered. The top three findings include: (1) gender was the strongest predictor of survival, with females having significantly higher survival rates than males, (2) passenger class strongly influenced survival, with first-class passengers having much higher survival probability, and (3) social and family-related features such as family size and title also played an important role in survival outcomes.

 (2) Data Quality Assessment (80+ words)

The dataset contained several data quality issues including missing values in key columns such as Age, Embarked, and Cabin. Age was partially missing and required intelligent imputation using median values grouped by passenger class and gender to preserve data patterns. Embarked was filled using the mode since it is a categorical feature. The Cabin column had excessive missing values, so instead of direct imputation, a derived feature (has_cabin and deck) was created. Additionally, feature inconsistencies such as text-based categories required encoding before analysis. These strategies ensured that no important information was lost while maintaining data integrity and improving usability for machine learning.

 (3) Feature Engineering Rationale (80+ words)

Several new features were engineered to improve predictive performance. Family size was created by combining SibSp and Parch to represent total family members aboard, while is_alone was derived to capture solo travelers. Title was extracted from passenger names to represent social status, grouped into common and rare categories to reduce complexity. Age was converted into age groups (Child, Teen, Adult, Senior) to capture non-linear survival patterns. Fare per person was introduced to normalize ticket cost across families. Deck information was extracted from Cabin to provide location-based insight. Fare binning was used to categorize continuous fare values into ordinal groups for better interpretability.

 (4) Key Statistical Findings (120+ words)

Survival analysis revealed strong demographic and socio-economic patterns. Females had a survival rate of approximately 74%, while males had only around 19%, making gender the strongest predictor of survival. Passenger class also had a major impact: first-class passengers had survival rates close to 63%, whereas third-class passengers had significantly lower survival rates around 24%. Age analysis showed that children had higher survival probabilities compared to adults and seniors. Family size also influenced survival, with small families (2–4 members) showing better survival rates than individuals or large families. Embarked location had a smaller but noticeable effect, with passengers from certain ports showing slightly higher survival rates. Overall, socio-economic status and gender were the dominant factors influencing survival outcomes.

 (5) Visualization Insights (100+ words)

Multiple visualizations were used to understand relationships between variables. Bar charts showed survival rates across passenger classes and gender, clearly highlighting the dominance of female survival and first-class advantage. KDE plots illustrated age distribution differences between survivors and non-survivors, showing that younger passengers had better survival chances. Boxplots revealed fare distribution differences across passenger classes, with first-class passengers having significantly higher fare ranges. Heatmaps provided a combined view of survival across class and gender, showing that first-class females had the highest survival probability. Family size vs survival plots indicated that moderate family sizes had better outcomes. Among all visualizations, the class-gender heatmap was the most informative for prediction.

 (6) Feature Selection Recommendation (80+ words)

For machine learning modeling in Week 5, the most important features to include are: Sex (encoded), Pclass, Age, Fare, Family Size, Is Alone, Title, and Embarked. These features capture demographic, socio-economic, and behavioral aspects of passengers. Sex and Pclass are the strongest predictors of survival based on correlation analysis. Family-based features provide insight into social structure, while Title adds socio-economic context. Age and Fare contribute numerical variability essential for model learning. Embarked provides slight but useful variation. Less important or redundant features such as Passenger ID, Ticket, and raw Name should be excluded to avoid noise and overfitting.

 (7) Reflection (80+ words)

The most challenging part of this analysis was feature engineering and deciding how to transform raw variables into meaningful predictive features. Handling missing values in a way that preserved data distribution required careful consideration, especially for Age and Cabin. The biggest surprise was how strongly gender influenced survival outcomes, far more than expected compared to other features. If I were to improve this project, I would experiment with advanced feature selection techniques such as recursive feature elimination and also try multiple machine learning models to compare performance. Additionally, I would perform cross-validation to ensure model robustness and avoid overfitting.